Polyketides are a large family of structurally complex natural products including compounds with important bioactivities (1). Examples include antibiotics such as erythromycin (2), actinorhodin (3), and tetracenomycin (4); chemotherapeutics such as doxorubicin (5), resistomycin (6), and mithramycin (7); cholesterol-lowering drugs such as lovastatin (8); antioxidants such as resveratrol (9); and toxins (T-toxin) and carcinogens (aﬂatoxin B1) (10) (Figure 1). At the center of polyketide biosynthesis is the polyketide synthase (PKS), a multidomain enzyme complex that produces a huge variety of polyketides via controlled variation of building blocks, chain lengths, and chain modiﬁcation such as reduction and cyclization. Considering the high sequence homology between PKSs and fatty acid synthases (FASs), a fascinating question is how PKSs and FASs exhibit such different enzyme capacities, as reﬂected from the vastly diverse products these two megasynthases biosynthesize. On the basis of domain architecture, there are at least four distinct PKSs: modular type I, iterative type I, type II, and type III (11). There are many excellent reviews of modular PKSs (13–19). In comparison, iterative type I PKSs, often found in fungi, contain a single module that catalyzes polyketide chain elongation and modiﬁ- cation in an iterative fashion; they can be further divided into reducing and nonreducing PKSs (NRPKSs), depending on the presence or absence, respectively, of reducing domains (Figure 1b). Type II PKSs, often found in Streptomyces species, consist of ﬁve to ten stand-alone domains that conduct iterative chain elongation followed by reduction or cyclization to biosynthesize aromatic polyketides (Figure 1a). Type III PKSs, often from plants, use a single domain to conduct a limited set of chain elongations followed by cyclization to afford plant aromatic polyketides such as resveratrol (20). CHEMICAL LOGIC OF FATTY ACID SYNTHASES FASs consist of 7 conserved protein domains that catalyze >50 reactions en route to the ﬁnal fatty acid product (Figure 2). Starting with malonyl-CoA (coenzyme A) as the basic building block, malonyl-CoA:ACP transacylase (MAT) primes the acyl carrier protein (ACP) by transferring mal- onate from malonyl-CoA to the phosphopantetheine (PPT) (Figure 3) group of ACP. PPT is covalently linked to a conserved Ser of ACP. Next, the starter unit, acetyl-CoA, is transacylated to

This is followed by KS-catalyzed decarboxylative Claisen condensation between the KS-bound acyl group and malonyl-ACP, in which decarboxy- lation is a strong driving force for C–C bond formation. Following each elongation step, the ACP-bound chain is further reduced by NADPH-dependent ketoreductase (KR), dehydrated by dehydratase (DH), and reduced by NADPH-dependent enoylreductase to afford a fully reduced aliphatic chain. Chain elongation and modiﬁcation are conducted iteratively, until thioesterase (TE) hydrolyzes the fatty acyl-ACP thioester bond and releases the fatty acid product.

On the basis of domain architecture, FASs can be classiﬁed as type I or type II (Figure 2). Type I FASs are found mainly in mammals and fungi as well as certain bacteria. In type I FAS, the seven FAS catalytic domains are covalently linked and exist as a single polypeptide. In comparison, type II FASs are found in plants, animal mitochondria, and bacteria, where each FAS catalytic domain exists as a stand-alone enzyme. Further, different from type I FASs, type II FASs often contain a priming KS, two KSs, and two DHs (21). Because of the importance of fatty acids to basic survival, each FAS domain is highly conserved structurally and functionally from bacteria (type II) to mammals (type I). FAS domains have been validated as drug targets against obesity, diabetes (22), and cancer (23), as well as infectious diseases such as tuberculosis (24, 25). Recently, FAS has also been a target for engineered biofuels (26). There are many excellent reviews of both type I and type II FAS structures (21, 27), and Crosby & Crump (28) have reported on the structural enzymology of ACP of both PKSs and FASs.

3. POLY-β-KETONE MIMICS AS CHEMICAL PROBES OF AROMATIC POLYKETIDE SYNTHASES The intermediates of type II PKSs and NRPKSs are highly reactive poly-β-ketones 1 (Figures 2 and 3) that are prone to spontaneous aldol cyclization and cannot be isolated (29). Consequently, past studies of aromatic PKS intermediates are speculative and largely based on apo PKS structures (30–41). Furthermore, past enzymology studies of PKSs often utilized acyl-SNACs (42), which are truncated analogs of PPT (Figure 3). It is not clear if the full-length PPT is necessary to convey enzyme activity and regiospeciﬁcity. To address the need for a stable polyketide mimic with the full-length PPT attached, a series of ﬁrst-generation polyketide mimics 2–6 were recently synthesized (Figure 3a) (43). Owing to substantial differences between isoxazole probes and natural poly-β-ketone substrates, the Tsai and Vanderwal groups collaborated to generate probes that more closely mimicked native substrates. The oxetane ring has achieved a lofty status in medicinal chemistry over the past decade, owing primarily to the efforts of Bull et al. (44). Although slightly larger overall than a carbonyl group, the oxetane oxygen lone pairs are similarly oriented, allowing oxetane to serve as a carbonyl isostere (8–14) (Figure 3b). In addition, a propionyl-PPT mimic 7 has been synthesized to aid in the struc- tural visualization of polyketide priming (Sections 4.2 and 8.1), as well as two mechanism-based crosslinkers to investigate protein-protein interactions in these megasynthases (45) (Section 6) (Figure 3c). As detailed below, the cocrystal structures of these mimics with PKSs provided un- precedented information about the mechanism and regiospeciﬁcity of aromatic PKSs. 4. Malonyl-Acyl Carrier Protein Transacylase

MAT is part of type II FASs in Actinomycetes and loads the malonyl extender unit onto ACP. The importance of MAT for type II PKSs depends on the relative protein concentrations of MAT, KS/CLF, and ACP as well as speciﬁc PKSs (59–66). Keatinge-Clay et al. (65) described the Streptomyces coelicolor MAT structure, which is composed of two domains: a larger core subdomain that is similar to an α/β-hydrolase fold and a smaller ferredoxin fold–containing subdomain. Active site Ser is located between the two subdomains at the “nucleophilic elbow” that enhances its ability to undergo nucleophilic attack on malonyl-CoA to form the malonyl-Ser intermediate. 1. In type II FAS, there are three KSs: the priming KS (FabH) and two elongating KSs (FabB and FabF) (47). One ACP is shared by all three KSs (47). In comparison, many type II PKSs do not have a priming KS. However, when a priming KS is present, there are often two ACPs, one for the priming KS and the other for the elongating KS (48). The biggest difference is the CLF, which is essentially an inactivated KS domain (49, 50). 2. Regiospeciﬁcity is drastically different between type II FASs and PKSs (51). 3. In type II FASs, two DHs, FabA and FabZ, catalyze dehydration of fatty acyl chains (52, 53). Type II PKSs do not have a DH; rather, KS/CLF preassembles the linear poly-β-ketone intermediate 1, followed by the action of KR and/or ARO/CYC (54). 4. Priming Ketosynthase Two priming KS structures have been reported: ZhuH of R1128 PKS that biosynthesizes polyke- tides with acetyl-, propionyl-, and butyryl-starter units (40) and DpsC of doxorubicin PKS that biosynthesizes only polyketide products with the propionyl starter unit (Figure 5a,b) (46, 67, 68). Similar to all KS crystal structures from type I and II FASs and PKSs, ZhuH and DpsC have a highly conserved thiolase fold (20), which consists of two copies of a αβαβα fold that forms a ﬁve- layered core (2α-5β-2α-5β-2α) with extensive connecting loops (Figure 5a,b). All KS domains have extensive dimer interfaces. ZhuH, like all fatty acid priming KSs, has the catalytic triad His-Asn-Cys (Figure 5a). Active site Cys undergoes nucleophilic attack on the starter unit thioester bond, forming a new cysteine- linked thioester adduct via a tetrahedral intermediate. Malonyl-ACP then binds KS, which is decarboxylated to form an enolate that undergoes nucleophilic attack on the acyl-cysteine thioester to produce the elongated polyketide-ACP product.

In contrast, DpsC is unique, serving both as priming KS and AT, with a Ser-His catalytic dyad that is very different from all other KSs (46, 67, 68) (Figure 5b). The cocrystal structures of DpsC bound with starter unit mimic 7 and malonate mimic 8 have been solved, showing that its overall structure overlaps well with both ZhuH and the Escherichia coli fatty acid priming KS FabH. For all other KSs, the active site Ser overlaps with the active site Cys. Interestingly, the active site Ser-His dyad also overlaps well with other AT domains of PKS and FAS (Figure 5b), indicating that the unique activity of AT may originate from a Cys to Ser mutation of an ancient priming KS. The cocrystal structure of DpsC bound with oxetane-malonate mimic 8 has been used to identify a potential oxyanion hole that is different from other KSs (Figure 5c), which may allow for decarboxylative Claisen condensation (KS activity). The type II PKS KR exists as a tetramer (37, 73), and each monomer contains a single short-chain dehydrogenase/reductase fold (Figure 7a). The cofactor NADPH is bound in a conserved groove characteristic of a Rossmann fold (74). The polyketide substrate-binding pocket consists of a large cleft formed by regions between α6−α7 and α4–α5 (Figure 7a). Inhibitor-bound as well as polyketide mimic–bound structures of ActKR, HedKR, and DoxKR also revealed that KR can exist with at least two different conformations (38). The open and closed forms differ in the α6−α7 region (Figure 7a), which is a unique feature in type II PKS KRs that is not observed in type I PKS or FAS KRs (75, 76); it deﬁnes half of the substrate-binding pocket and may inﬂuence KR regiospeciﬁcity (discussed in detail in Section 8.3).

The KR active site tetrad consists of Asn-Ser-Tyr-Lys (37, 38, 73) that is located near the nicotinamide ring of NADPH, where Tyr and Lys form hydrogen bonds with the NADPH ribose and nicotinamide ring (Figure 7b). In both ActKR and HedKR structures, four crystalline water molecules form a hydrogen-bond network with Asn and Lys residues (Figure 7b). This extensive proton water-relay network is very similar to the one observed in E. coli FabG-NADP+ (77), leading to the hypothesis that the water-relay mechanism for FabG may also be applicable to ActKR (Figure 7b) (37, 38). Past studies suggested that type II PKS KR may promote ﬁrst-ring cyclization of the linear poly-β-ketone intermediate (Figure 4) (1 to 15) (78–80). In support of this hypothesis, ActKR has a strong preference for bicyclic compounds in vitro (38). Thus, type II PKS KRs have dif- ferent substrate speciﬁcities from those of FASs (81, 82), which prefer linear and monocyclic ketones. Docking simulations of ActKR with polyketide substrates show that, under the dual con- straints imposed by the ring structure of 15 and the three-point docking with the KR active site, the C9-carbonyl group of 15 is optimally positioned for ketoreduction for the C7–C12-cyclized polyketide. Aromatase/Cyclase Once poly-β-ketone intermediate 1 (Figure 4) reaches full length, there are ﬁve different scenarios of chain modiﬁcations (Figure 8a), as follows: Sequence homology between classes 1 and 5 signiﬁcantly varies in terms of overall sequence identity (15–80%), though it is much more consistent within each class (>80% for classes 1–2 and >50% for classes 3–4). Class 2 bridges the mono- and didomain ARO/CYCs evolutionarily. With the structures of four of ﬁve ARO/CYC classes solved, plus successful syntheses and ARO/CYC cocrystal structures with oxetane- and isoxazole-based polyketide mimics (Figure 3), much progress has been made toward understanding the mechanism of ARO/CYC-mediated cyclization. Regardless of mono- or didomain, each ARO/CYC domain consists of a helix-grip fold (85, 86), with a seven-stranded antiparallel β-sheet that partially surrounds (grips) a long α-helix (Figure 8a). The helical grip is topologically very similar to the hot-dog fold found in the fatty acid DH and fungal polyketide product template domains (PT domains) (described in detail in Section 7).

In FAS, the catalytic dyad of DHs FabA (87) and FabZ (52) consists of His and Asp/Glu, which mediate dehydration via an acid/base mechanism. In comparison, site-directed mutagenesis, ﬁve ARO/CYC crystal structures, and docking simulations indicate that the most likely active site residue is Arg69 (Tcm ARO/CYC numbering) (30–32, 39). Mutations of Arg abolish activity for Tcm, ZhuI, BexL, and StfQ ARO/CYCs, indicating the role of Arg is catalytic and not as a hydrogen bond donor. Researchers proposed a mechanism in which conserved active site Arg, Tyr, and Ser serve as acids and bases to promote cyclization and dehydration/aromatization (30–32, 39). Since the ﬁrst type II PKSs were sequenced and cloned 25 years ago (50), it has been well known that some ARO/CYCs contain two domains, yet the role of each domain had not been determined. Two didomain ARO/CYC structures, BexL and StfQ ARO/CYCs (32), share 32% sequence ho- mology, and each accepts a decaketide (20 carbons). However, StfQ promotes C7–C12 cyclization in the absence of KR, whereas BexL ARO/CYC promotes ﬁrst and second aromatizations follow- ing KR-mediated C7–C12 ﬁrst-ring cyclization (Figure 8a). Crystal structures and mutagenesis studies indicate that the C-terminal domain (but not the N domain) of StfQ is catalytic, whereas the N-terminal domain (but not the C domain) of BexL is catalytic. This important difference indicates that the C domain of StfQ catalyzes cyclization, whereas the N domain of BexL catalyzes aromatization. In the active domain of both ARO/CYCs, highly conserved Arg and Ser residues are present. Catalytic Efﬁciency: Type II Fatty Acid Synthase Versus Type II Polyketide Synthase

Whereas type I FASs have undergone detailed enzyme kinetic studies, the catalytic efﬁciency of type II FAS has not been systematically evaluated. The E. coli and S. coelicolor MATs have kcat of 1,580 and 450 s−1, respectively (63, 64, 88). The priming KS FabH (or KAS III) in Staphylococcus aureus has a kcat of 30 s−1 (89), whereas E. coli KAS I (FabB, elongating C4–14 acyl chains) and KAS II (FabF, elongating C16 acyl chain) have kcat values of 2 and 0.6 s−1, respectively (90–92). E. coli KR (FabG) and enoylreductase (FabI) have kcat values of 300 and 4.2 s−1, respectively (93, 94). Similar to type I FAS DH, type II FAS DH FabA and FabZ also equilibrate between hydroxylacyl, rather than enoylacyl, intermediates in the absence of downstream domains, with apparent values for kcat of 0.25 and 1 s−1, respectively (53). However, TE does not carry out the chain termination step in E. coli. Instead, glycerol-3-phosphate acyltransferase (PlsB) transfers the fatty acyl chain from ACP to glycerol-3-phosphate for cell membrane lipid biosynthesis. PlsB is a fast-acting enzyme (kcat ∼100 s−1) (95) that drives the FAS reaction forward (21). Therefore, chain elongation catalyzed by KAS II (FabF), especially during the last cycle where C14 acyl chain is elongated to the ﬁnal C16 chain, appears to be the rate-limiting step in type II FAS (90).

Compared with type II FAS (described above), the catalytic efﬁciency of type II PKS is dis- tinctly unique. The enzyme kinetics of type II actinorhodin PKS was elucidated ﬁrst by Khosla and colleagues (64, 66, 96). A series of studies (59–63) followed in which each PKS domain was puriﬁed. Highly consistent results from two distinct assays conﬁrmed that the rates of ACP self- malonylation, acetyl primer loading, and polyketide chain elongation are dependent on protein- protein interactions and, by extension, the concentration of each PKS domain. Subsequent ketore- duction, cyclization, aromatization, and chain release may be much faster than chain elongation (61, 79). Therefore, protein-protein interactions in type II PKS not only are important for sub- strate speciﬁcity but also may play a key role in precisely timing each catalytic event that eventually affects the product outcome. 5. STRUCTURAL CONSERVATION: AROMATASE/CYCLASE VERSUS PRODUCT TEMPLATE VERSUS DEHYDRATASE

Type II PKS ARO/CYC contains a helix-grip fold; in comparison, all FAS DHs (such as E. coli FabA) and fungal polyketide PT domains contain two hot-dog folds, either as a didomain enzyme or a dimer of two monodomains (87, 120) (Figure 10). Helix-grip folds and hot-dog folds are topologically different but similar in shape. However, the central helix is tucked against the β- sheets in FabA, thus precluding the formation of an interior pocket between the β-sheet and central helix αC (Figure 10a). In comparison, the central helix for both ARO/CYC (Figure 10b) and PT (Figure 10c) is off to the side of the β-sheet, creating an interior pocket that protects highly reactive poly-β-ketone intermediates that are characteristic of aromatic PKSs. Why is the double hot-dog/helix-grip shape conserved across DHs, PTs, and ARO/CYCs, which share no sequence homology? Both mammalian FAS and MAS structures show that the DH-KS didomains are key to architecture stability (Figure 12a) (121). If the complex architecture of type II PKSs and NRPKSs is similar to that of type I FASs, the structural similarity among DHs, PTs, and ARO/CYCs suggests that the interaction of ARO/CYCs and PTs with upstream KS may be analogous to the FAS DH-KS interaction. The conserved presence of the Arg-Lys-rich region at the surface of DHs, PTs, and ARO/CYCs also indicates that these domains interact with electronegatively charged ACP with similar electrostatic interactions (Figure 10b,c). REGIOSPECIFICITIES OF FATTY ACID AND AROMATIC POLYKETIDE SYNTHASES 8.1. Starter Unit Speciﬁcity

The SAT domain of most (but not all) NRPKSs determines starter speciﬁcity, ranging from acetyl- to hexanoyl-CoA (122–126). In contrast, the MAT domain involved in type II FASs and PKSs is responsible only for extender unit speciﬁcity (21). For starter unit speciﬁcity, the priming KS of type II FASs (FabH) is highly speciﬁc for acetyl-CoA, whereas the situation is much more compli- cated for type II PKS. A comparison of ZhuH (acetyl, propionyl, and butyryl), E. coli FabH (acetyl), and Mycobacterium tuberculosis FabH (palmitoyl) indicates that several residues at the bottom of the substrate pocket may be responsible for the observed starter unit speciﬁcity (40). However, single and multiple mutations of these residues resulted in no change of starter unit speciﬁcity for ZhuH, as determined by in vitro enzyme assays (S.C. Tsai & C. Khosla, unpublished data). Rather, the starter unit speciﬁcity of ZhuH may arise from the supply of different acyl-CoAs in vivo.

The active site of DpsC is structurally and sequentially homologous to many ATs involved in natural product biosynthesis (67) (Figure 5b) (Section 4.2). Sequence alignment of DpsC with its structural/sequence homologs showed a clear correlation between pocket-deﬁning residues and substrate size. However, for smaller substrates (such as acetyl-, propionyl-, and butyryl-CoA), Jackson et al. (127) found that DpsC is promiscuous. Consistent with assay results, a series of DpsC cocrystal structures bound with acetyl-, propionyl-, and butyryl-CoA showed no difference in substrate binding (127). This accords with in vivo genetic knockout experiments by Bao et al. (67) showing that DpsC alone cannot convey the observed propionyl speciﬁcity. Propionyl-CoA is selected as the starter unit only when DpsC (priming KS/AT), DpsD (MAT), and DpsG (ACP) are all present, suggesting that protein-protein interactions among DpsC, DpsD, and DpsG are important for starter unit selectivity. 8.2. Chain Length Speciﬁcity

Chain length speciﬁcity of types I and II FASs and PKSs vary signiﬁcantly. For priming KSs, ZhuH of R1128 PKS and fatty acid FabH from E. coli, Streptococcus pneumoniae, and Streptomyces glaucescens strongly prefer C2–C4 acyl-CoA (40, 89), the Bacillus subtilis FabH prefers branched acyl-CoA (128), and the M. tuberculosis FabH prefers much longer chains such as myristoyl-CoA (129). For elongating KSs, ActKS/CLF and TcmKS/CLF extend the polyketide chain to 16 and 24 carbons (70), respectively; by contrast, the E. coli FabB and FabF prefer C4–C14 and C14–C16 substrates (90). The observed chain length speciﬁcity of each KS domain can be explained by the size and shape of the KS substrate-binding channel, which can be divided into two halves, corresponding to the substrate- and PPT-binding regions (Figure 6; Section 4.3). Whereas the binding pockets of FAS KS domains are hydrophobic and promote fatty acid binding (89, 114, 130, 131), the acyl-binding pockets of PKS KSs are amphipathic and allow hydrogen-bonding interactions with the growing poly-β-ketone chain (40, 69, 132, 133). Signiﬁcantly, mutations of four CLF residues that deﬁne the bottom of the acyl pocket successfully switched the chain length speciﬁcity of ActKS/CLF and TcmKS/CLF (70). Although this result indicates that CLF alone determines chain length speciﬁcity (70), past reports and preliminary data showed that chain length speciﬁcity is determined not only by KS/CLF, but also by downstream KR and ARO/CYC (30–32, 34–39, 41, 70, 96, 134). Reduction: Stereospeciﬁcity

Compared with type II fatty acid and polyketide KRs, stereospeciﬁcities of type I fatty acid and modular polyketide KRs have been much more extensively studied (27). Stereoselective signature motifs for modular PKS KRs were previously proposed to be LDD (75, 76). The presence of these motifs predicts formation of the 3R stereomer (or D stereomer), whereas their absence predicts the 3S stereomer (or L stereomer). Multiple research groups have conducted extensive work on the stereospeciﬁcity of modular PKSs (14, 17, 136). Sequence alignment indicates that the LDD motif corresponds to the LRD motif in mammalian FAS KR domains and is therefore predicted to produce the R stereochemistry. Consistent with this prediction, mammalian FAS produces a (3R)-hydroxyacyl moiety (137). Similarly, the LDD motif and corresponding stereospeciﬁcity have been reported for type II FAS (FabG) and tropinone reductase (92, 138). In contrast, type II polyketide KRs may be one of the few short-chain dehydrogenase/reductase members that are nonselective during ketoreduction (139), producing a mixture of S- and R- mutactin when MAT, KS/CLF, ACP, and KR are incubated in vitro or in vivo. Consequently, various studies have been unable to determine the C9 stereochemistry of mutactin, presumably ow- ing to the S and R mixture of stereomers (140). On the basis of their crystal structures (Section 4.4; Figure 7), nearly all type II KRs contain a unique motif corresponding to 94-XGG-96, which aligns with the LDD motif in modular type I PKS KRs (75, 76). In act KR, this motif corresponds to 94-PGG-96. Systematic mutations of the PGG motif in act KR conﬁrmed that wild-type Act KR has a 3:1 preference for S- versus R-tetralol in vitro (38). In comparison, the single P94L mu- tant resulted in complete abolishment of R-tetralol oxidation activity, while retaining full catalytic

Thus, stereospeciﬁc reduction of ACP-bound polyketide is inﬂuenced at least partially by steric constraints imposed by the pocket residues. Following this principle, the stereospeciﬁcity of ActKR was switched from S dominant to R speciﬁc after screening active site mutants, a ﬁrst success for KR engineering (36). 8.4. Cyclization Speciﬁcity

Unlike fatty acids, polyketides have diverse cyclization patterns. For the past few decades, a mystery persisted regarding how fungal polyketides speciﬁcally adopt the F-fold pattern (C2–C7, C4–C9, or C6–C11 ﬁrst-ring cyclization) (Figures 9b and 10c; Section 5.2), whereas bacterial aromatic polyketides adopt the S-fold pattern (C7–C12 or C9–C14 ﬁrst-ring cyclization) (Figure 10b; Section 4.5) (29). Now, with the full series of crystal structures available for both ARO/CYCs and PTs, a molecular basis of cyclization speciﬁcity can be established. Despite their similar topologies, the most striking difference between PTs and ARO/CYCs is the shape of their interior pocket, which corresponds to their distinct cyclization speciﬁcities (Figure 10). On the basis of apo and cocrystal structures of PksA PT (33, 105), the linear poly-β-ketone intermediate binds PT with a fully extended linear conformation, which is then slightly kinked in the cyclization chamber to promote the F-fold cyclization pattern (Figure 10c; Section 5.2). In comparison, on the basis of the apo and cocrystal structures of ARO/CYCs (especially the full series of mimic- bound WhiE cocrystal structures) (30–32, 39; T. Valentic, J. Barajas, J.J. Recent revelations from crystallographic analyses of type I and type II FASs and PKSs have raised awareness of the extraordinary architecture of these megasynthases and offer a new perspective in visualizing some of the unsolved questions concerning polyketide biosynthesis. Structural and enzymological studies of aromatic PKSs, including type II PKS and NRPKS, have shed light on the observed product speciﬁcity (30–41, 43, 45, 65, 70, 105, 106, 127; G.B. Moreno, G. Shakya, J. Barajas, J.J. La Clair, M.D. Burkart, S.C. Tsai, submitted manuscript; J.J. Milligan, J. Lee, M.D. Burkart, S.C. Tsai, submitted manuscript). The availability of poly-β-ketone mimics further helps in visualizing these enzymes in action (43). Now, protein structural motifs can be correlated with variations in starter unit, chain length, reduction, and cyclization patterns of these diverse natural products. Because of the dynamic nature of multidomain PKS complexes, X-ray crystallography, if at all successful, may capture only one snapshot of this transient complex, but other techniques such as electron microscopy have been signiﬁcantly successful in elucidating protein-protein inter- actions in modular PKSs (116). Efforts in combining chemical biology, NMR, molecular dynamics simulations, and crystallography have successfully visualized how ACP interacts with its partner enzymes (45). Similar NMR and electron microscopic studies for aromatic PKSs will likely be conducted in the future, so the importance of protein-protein interactions to product outcome can be elucidated. Finally, the structural information gleaned from these studies is expected to serve as a blueprint to guide future bioengineering efforts on PKSs.
